    criticRating: "Exceptional",
    review: {
      themes: ["estrangement", "narcissism", "legacy", "manipulation", "performance", "grief", "ambition", "reconciliation"],
      mood: ["elegiac", "wry", "disquieting"],
      fullReview: "Sisters Nora and Agnes are abruptly pulled back into the chaotic orbit of their estranged father, Gustav, a once-revered auteur director desperate to orchestrate his cinematic resurrection. When Nora, a fiercely independent and highly acclaimed stage actor, decisively rejects his offer to star in his intensely personal new project, Gustav retaliates with the petulance of a wounded god. He callously casts an eager, young Hollywood starlet in the role explicitly written for and about his daughter. As the cameras roll and production begins to consume their lives, the two sisters find themselves drawn into a surreal, inescapable collision of unhealed family trauma, artistic exploitation, and decades of unresolved resentments.\n\nJoachim Trier and his longtime co-writer Eskil Vogt have spent decades meticulously mapping the existential anxieties and quiet despair of the Scandinavian middle class, but here they turn their surgical precision toward the very act of storytelling itself. The film operates on two distinct frequencies, succeeding brilliantly as both a biting, inside-baseball satire of the cinematic ego and a profoundly moving exploration of familial neglect. It asks an age-old, deeply uncomfortable question: is monumental art ever worth the human collateral required to forge it? The picture leans into the uncomfortable reality that terrible parents can make transcendent art, and that forgiveness from their children is not always a necessary, or even possible, conclusion.\n\nStellan Skarsgård delivers a monolithic, towering performance as Gustav. He radiates the exact kind of weaponized, intellectual charm that allows brilliant men to leave a trail of emotional wreckage behind them without ever having to apologize or face the consequences. Skarsgård refuses to play Gustav as a simple villain. Instead, he constructs a tragic, pathetic narcissist who genuinely, foolishly believes that capturing truth on a camera lens somehow absolves him of completely ignoring it in his own living room. The comedic timing he brings to the character’s moments of immense self-pity is nothing short of masterful.\n\nOpposite him, Renate Reinsve continues to prove that she is one of the most intuitively gifted, fascinating actors working today. Her portrayal of Nora is tightly wound, vibrating constantly with a toxic cocktail of disgust, righteous anger, and a desperate, buried yearning for a father who only knows how to communicate his love through a viewfinder. Elle Fanning, stepping into the perilous role of the eager American starlet Rachel, provides a brilliant and necessary counter-melody. Fanning’s wide-eyed earnestness slowly and methodically peels back to reveal a sharp, calculating, and opportunistic edge, perfectly highlighting the predatory nature of the international film industry. Inga Ibsdotter Lilleaas anchors the supporting cast as Agnes, the seemingly stable sibling whose own psychological cracks begin to aggressively splinter when she is forced to mediate the war between Nora and Gustav.\n\nKasper Tuxen’s cinematography captures Oslo in a crisp, melancholic autumnal light. He creates a visual language that relies heavily on stark contrasts, deliberately juxtaposing the warm, intimate, physically grounded chaos of the theater world Nora inhabits with the cold, imposing, deeply artificial environments of Gustav’s film sets. The score by Hania Rani adds a delicate, haunting texture that elevates the emotional stakes without ever attempting to manipulate the audience.\n\nThe narrative pacing occasionally meanders during the second act, specifically when the script takes a slightly too deep, indulgent dive into the secondary mechanics of the film-within-a-film production. However, it course-corrects brilliantly and brutally in the final stretch. The climax strips away all the cinematic artifice, forcing the characters into a space where no script can save them. What remains with the viewer is the uneasy, deafening silence of a fractured family that simply cannot be neatly edited into a comfortable resolution. This is a bruised, beautiful, and deeply cynical portrait of inheritance—not of wealth or talent, but of inescapable emotional debt."
    }
