    criticRating: "Exceptional",
    review: {
      themes: ["surveillance", "resistance", "disappearance", "complicity", "fatherhood", "dictatorship", "identity", "carnival"],
      mood: ["suffocating", "electric", "disquieting"],
      fullReview: "Brazil, 1977. The military dictatorship is eight years into its long grip on the country, Carnival is consuming Recife in noise and sequins and heat, and a man who goes by at least two names is trying not to be found. Marcelo — or Armando, or whatever name is most useful at a given checkpoint — is a technology expert with a past that the state would very much like to account for. He has come to this city during its most chaotic week to find his son. What he finds instead is that the chaos offers neither the cover he needs nor the escape he imagined.\n\nKleber Mendonça Filho has spent his career building a cinema that is inseparable from Recife — its architecture, its class tensions, its particular quality of light and noise and threat. With The Secret Agent, he does something he has not quite done before: he borrows the skeleton of genre filmmaking, the fugitive thriller, the cat-and-mouse procedural, and fills it with the specific political weight of a country whose recent history remains a wound that has not been allowed to fully close. The result is a film that functions as a legitimate thriller — there are chases, there are close calls, there are rooms where the wrong person says the wrong thing — while simultaneously refusing to let genre machinery replace political consciousness.\n\nWagner Moura carries the film inside his body as much as on his face. This is a performance that requires Moura to be simultaneously hyperalert and deliberately opaque, a man who has learned to disappear even while standing in a crowd. The particular skill of it is how little Moura performs: the watchfulness is in the eyes, the tension in the way he occupies doorways, the calculation in every conversation where the wrong word would end everything. It is the kind of work that looks simple and is anything but, and the film earns its weight almost entirely through the credibility Moura brings to a man for whom every encounter is a potential betrayal.\n\nCarnival is not backdrop here — it is an argument. Mendonça Filho understands that a state celebrating excess while conducting disappearances in the adjacent dark is not a paradox but a strategy, and he shoots the festival with a kind of gorgeous menace that refuses easy beauty. The noise that should mask things instead amplifies them. The crowd that should provide anonymity becomes its own surveillance. Evgenia Alexandrova's cinematography handles this with uncommon precision: the film feels simultaneously wide open — Recife breathing and burning and dancing — and completely sealed, as if the walls of a particular historical moment have closed around everyone in the frame.\n\nThe supporting cast is populated by faces that belong to this story rather than to any genre template. Maria Fernanda Cândido brings a cool, controlled intelligence to her scenes that complicates Moura's every interaction. Gabriel Leone finds the precise register of a young man who understands more than he has been told. And Udo Kier's presence — as a German contact who exists in the film's margins — functions as a quiet reminder that authoritarian networks have no national boundaries. The international dimensions of the dictatorship, propped up by Cold War alliances and quiet foreign participation, are embedded in the casting rather than spelled out in dialogue.\n\nAt 161 minutes, the film asks for patience, and most of what it asks for is returned. The longer stretches are not padding — they are about accumulation, about what it feels like to move through a city where every transaction carries risk, where time itself has become hostile. There are sequences in the final hour that achieve a specific kind of dread that the thriller genre almost never reaches because most thrillers are too interested in resolution. Mendonça Filho is interested in something else: what it costs to survive inside a machine built to prevent survival.\n\nThe film is dedicated, in spirit if not explicitly, to the people who did not make it through this particular period of Brazilian history — those who were detained, tortured, disappeared. The genre elements are not there to entertain audiences away from this reality. They are there to make it visceral, immediate, impossible to intellectualize into abstraction. A political film that is also genuinely tense is doing something harder than either a political film or a thriller alone. This one earns both descriptions.\n\nViewers who go in expecting clean resolution will find themselves in the wrong film. Viewers who understand that some histories do not resolve — they simply stop — will find one of the most purposeful works to emerge from Brazilian cinema in years."
    }
