    review: {
      themes: ["belonging", "loneliness", "performance", "authenticity", "displacement", "connection", "grief"],
      mood: ["tender", "wry", "intimate"],
      fullReview: "Phillip Vanderploeg is a middle-aged American actor stuck in Tokyo with a modest resumé, a dwindling bank account, and the particular kind of rootlessness that follows a person who has spent too long playing versions of someone else. When he stumbles into work at a rental family agency — a real phenomenon in Japan where people hire stand-ins for weddings, funerals, office events, anywhere a person needs family they do not have — he discovers something unexpected: he is genuinely good at it. Better at being someone else than he has been at being himself for years.\n\nDirector Hikari, working from a script she co-wrote with Stephen Blahut, treats this premise with more intelligence than its surface charm might suggest. Rental Family is not a fish-out-of-water comedy or a culture-clash film, though it has elements of both. What it actually is, underneath the warmth and the Tokyo streetscapes and the occasionally absurd professional situations, is a film about the serious human need to feel witnessed. The clients who hire Phillip — a man who wants a stranger to attend his mother's funeral, a family who needs a grandfather figure for a child's school day, a woman who simply wants someone to sit with her in a bar — are not lonely in any simple or pitiable sense. They have constructed what they need from available materials. Phillip is one of those materials, and the film watches with genuine curiosity as the transaction slowly becomes something else.\n\nBrendan Fraser gives his best performance in years here, and the comparison to his Oscar-winning work is instructive: where that role required maximalism, this one asks him to be still. Phillip is a man whose professional instinct is to fill space, and the film keeps catching him in moments where he stops doing that — where something real interrupts the performance and he does not immediately know what to do with it. Fraser handles these transitions without announcing them, and the restraint is the point. There is a quality of earned exhaustion in the performance, as if Phillip has spent so long being accommodating that genuine feeling has become the harder act.\n\nTakehiro Hira as Shinji Tada, Phillip's supervisor and eventually something more complicated than a colleague, anchors the Japanese side of the film with a precision that never strays into stereotype. Hira is playing a man who has made peace with the architecture of his own life — or believes he has — and the film watches that belief get quietly tested. Their dynamic, two men in the business of simulating connection who have both stopped noticing what they personally lack, is the film's most interesting relationship, and Hikari gives it room to develop without rushing it toward resolution.\n\nThe score by Jónsi and Alex Somers does exactly what a score should do in a film like this: it makes the spaces between scenes feel inhabited. Their work tends toward the delicate end of things, never overwhelming a moment that is trying to breathe. Takuro Ishizaka's cinematography captures Tokyo with affection but without tourism — this is a city where people live their complicated lives, not a backdrop.\n\nWhere Rental Family is less sure of itself is in its structure. The episodic nature of Phillip's assignments, which gives the film much of its variety and humor, also makes the middle section feel slightly meandering. Several of the client scenarios are excellent on their own terms; not all of them deepen the central argument. The film earns its ending but works a little harder to get there than it should.\n\nThese are real limitations, but they do not undo what the film does right, which is substantial. Hikari has made a film that takes seriously the idea that manufactured closeness might shade into the genuine article — not as a trick or a twist, but as a quiet, incremental truth about how people actually find their way toward each other. Anyone who has ever felt most themselves while playing a role will recognize something here. The film does not resolve that paradox. It just sits with it, warmly, for nearly two hours, which turns out to be enough."
    }
