    criticRating: "Exceptional",
    review: {
      themes: ["power", "accountability", "narcissism", "complicity", "legacy", "performance", "predation"],
      mood: ["suffocating", "hypnotic", "unsettling"],
      fullReview: "Lydia Tár is, by every measurable standard, at the summit of the world. The first woman to serve as chief conductor of the Berlin Philharmonic, a celebrated composer, a bestselling author, a living monument to serious music — she is exactly the kind of figure that institutions construct their prestige around, and she knows it. As TÁR opens, she is preparing to record what should be the crowning achievement of her career: a complete Mahler Fifth. But something is already gathering at the edges. An assistant has gone quiet in a particular way. Emails have been forwarded to people who have no business receiving them. The foundations are shifting before the first crack is visible.\n\nTodd Field\'s film, his first in sixteen years, opens with an extended real-time interview — Lydia seated onstage at the New Yorker Festival, in conversation with the actual journalist Adam Gopnik. It lasts nearly ten minutes and it is one of the most audacious gambits in recent memory. No plot, no incident, just a character talking about music, power, and herself with the fluency of someone who has long since stopped distinguishing between the two. By the time the scene ends, viewers know exactly who Lydia Tár is — her brilliance, her vanity, the casual cruelty in how she commands every room she enters — and they have been given no easy instruction on how to feel about her.\n\nThat refusal to instruct is what separates TÁR from the film it could have lazily been. This is not a #MeToo fable with a satisfying arc. It does not move toward catharsis or justice in any conventional shape. What Field is more interested in — what makes the film genuinely disturbing — is the ecosystem that Tár inhabits: the assistants who enable her, the board members who protect their investment, the colleagues who look away, the institutions that confuse excellence with permission. The abuse of power here is not depicted as aberrant. It is shown to be structural, almost atmospheric, the natural condition of environments built around genius and prestige.\n\nCate Blanchett\'s performance is the kind that rewrites what a film performance can do. It is not built on moments of visible anguish or explosive release — the temptations of lesser work. It is built on comportment. The way Tár holds a baton when she is not conducting, like she is always half-conducting. The way she moves through an apartment she is thinking of buying, assessing it the way she assesses musicians — for what it might offer her. The way a flicker of awareness passes across her face when she realizes something has already gone wrong, replaced almost immediately by the cold resolution not to let it alter her stride. Blanchett does not play a villain. She plays a person who has organized the entire architecture of her life around the conviction that her gifts exempt her from ordinary obligations — and who is only now, and only partially, beginning to reckon with what that has cost other people.\n\nFlorian Hoffmeister\'s cinematography is immaculate in its restraint. Berlin is rendered in cool grays and institutional blues — beautiful spaces that feel like they belong to the occupation rather than the occupant. The camera does not editorialize. It simply watches, often from distances that feel clinical, as if the film itself is maintaining professional detachment from its subject. This visual neutrality is a moral choice, and a brave one.\n\nHildur Guðnadóttir\'s score — built around the Mahler that Tár is preparing — functions less as emotional guidance than as ironic counterpoint. The grandeur of the music against the smallness of the behavior driving the film\'s central crisis creates a dissonance that lingers long after the final scene.\n\nThe last act has divided audiences, and not without reason. The film\'s resolution is elliptical, resistant to the satisfactions most narratives earn through consequence. But considered alongside everything the film has spent two and a half hours establishing — the way institutions absorb damage, the way powerful people land on their feet, the way prestige migrates rather than disappears — the ending is the only honest one available. It is not comfortable. Neither is the rest of TÁR.\n\nThis is a film for viewers who do not need to be told what to think of the person they are watching — and who can tolerate spending nearly three hours in intimate proximity with someone genuinely difficult to like, and genuinely impossible to dismiss."
    }
