    criticRating: "Masterpiece",
    review: {
      themes: ["faith", "complicity", "heritage", "guilt", "grief", "memory", "belonging"],
      mood: ["sparse", "disquieting", "contemplative"],
      fullReview: "Poland, 1962. A young woman named Anna has grown up inside a convent, knowing nothing of her life before its walls. Before she takes her final vows, the nuns ask her to visit her only living relative — an aunt she has never met. What that aunt tells her fractures the only identity Anna has ever possessed: her real name is Ida, she is Jewish, and her parents did not survive the war. What follows is a road film of sorts, the two women driving into the grey Polish countryside searching for graves that were never marked and answers that the living have spent twenty years not giving.\n\nPaweł Pawlikowski shot Ida in the Academy ratio — that near-square frame associated with cinema before widescreen became standard — and the decision is the film\'s most immediately striking formal quality. His compositions are relentlessly unusual. Characters are pushed to the bottom quarter of the frame, sometimes lower, the top two thirds given over to white winter skies, dark ceilings, the weight of empty rooms. It is disorienting at first and then, gradually, inescapable. The frame feels like a world in which people are small and what bears down on them from above — history, God, absence — is vast. No contemporary film uses negative space quite like this.\n\nThe black and white photography, shot across two different cinematographers (Ryszard Lenczewski and the then-unknown Łukasz Żal), has a texture that sits somewhere between vintage documentary and something closer to dream. There is grain in the shadows and a coldness to the light that suits a film about a country still digesting what was done on its soil and, in some cases, by its hands. The visual restraint never tips into aestheticism for its own sake — every formal choice is load-bearing.\n\nAgata Trzebuchowska plays Anna/Ida with almost no conventional technique on display, which sounds like a criticism and is the opposite. Her face in close-up becomes the film\'s primary emotional instrument — still, watchful, processing at a frequency the audience can sense but not quite name. She was a non-professional when cast, and the quality she brings to the role is exactly the kind of quality training tends to eliminate: the camera finds her rather than her finding the camera. When something crosses her face in a quiet scene, viewers lean forward.\n\nAgata Kulesza as Wanda is the counterweight, and it is a fully professional, deeply crafted performance. Wanda is a judge and a former Stalinist prosecutor — a woman who once handed down sentences she understood to be political theater — and who now drinks steadily and sleeps with men whose names she does not retain. Kulesza plays her without the self-pity the role might invite and without the redemption arc it might seem to promise. Wanda is intelligent, corrosive, funny in the bleak manner of someone who has discarded every comfort except irony, and she regards her niece\'s faith with something too complicated to be called contempt. The dynamic between the two women — the devout girl and the ruined atheist, bound by blood and by a shared catastrophe neither fully understands — is the film\'s engine, and it never runs on sentiment.\n\nAt 82 minutes, Ida is the rare short film that earns its brevity not through omission but through compression. Every scene contains more than it immediately yields. A conversation at a kitchen table carries three decades of national guilt. A shot of a young woman in a borrowed dress, hearing jazz for the first time, holds an entire argument about what faith costs and what the world costs. Pawlikowski trusts the audience to work, and the work is rewarding rather than punishing.\n\nThe film engages directly with Polish-Jewish relations during the German occupation without ever becoming a lecture or a thesis film. It is far too interested in its particular people for that. But the questions it raises — about who knew what, who benefited, who stayed silent — sit underneath every scene like a second floor that the characters are always aware of and the film never lets viewers forget. The countryside Anna and Wanda move through is not picturesque. It is a landscape with things buried in it.\n\nWhat Pawlikowski has made is a film about a person standing at the intersection of two histories and two identities, given almost no tools to navigate that intersection, and having to decide — with minimal information and in real time — what she actually is. That question remains genuinely open until the final frames, and the answer, such as it is, lands without fanfare. This is not a film that tells anyone what to feel. It puts them in a room and closes the door, and what stays with a person afterward is the particular quality of that silence."
    }
