    criticRating: "Great",
    review: {
      themes: ["loss", "desire", "time", "obsession", "displacement", "longing", "futurity"],
      mood: ["melancholic", "hypnotic", "restless"],
      fullReview: "Some films take years to make. This one took five, survived a fire that destroyed its sets, cycled through actors who came and went, and arrived at Cannes in 2004 still technically unfinished — Wong Kar-Wai editing on a laptop through the night before the premiere screening. The turbulence is not entirely invisible in the finished film, which is the source of both its richness and its frustration. 2046 is a work of genuine ambition straining at seams that do not always hold.\n\nChow Mo-wan — last seen at the end of In the Mood for Love, hollowing out a secret into a stone wall at Angkor Wat — is now a writer in a Singapore hotel, living in room 2047 next to a room he keeps trying to rent. He drinks. He gambles. He writes pulp science fiction. Women move through his life in succession: a magnetic card shark he desires without being able to fully reach; the hotel owner\'s daughter, slowly and painfully in love with a Japanese man her family forbids; another woman who shares the name of someone he lost. Each encounter circles the same absence. Each one ends in a different variety of incompletion.\n\nThe science fiction sections — set aboard a futuristic train perpetually bound for a place called 2046 where nothing ever changes — are Wong\'s most explicit statement of his themes, rendered in cool blues and lacquered reds, with androids who respond to human affection on a delay. The delay is the metaphor: these are machines processing feeling at a frequency that cannot match the speed of the person wanting. The sequences are visually stunning and conceptually interesting but they sit slightly apart from the film\'s warmer, more urgent sections. They feel like illustrations of what the rest of the film enacts. When cinema is working at full power, it does not need to illustrate its own arguments.\n\nWhat saves 2046 from becoming a beautiful but airless exercise is Zhang Ziyi. Her Bai Ling — a nightclub hostess who falls for Chow in a direct, un-hedged way that he cannot match — is the film\'s moral center, almost despite the film\'s intentions. She wants something and says so. She is humiliated by the wanting and refuses to pretend otherwise. Zhang plays the role with a rawness that cuts through the film\'s formal elegance like a sharp edge through silk. The scene in which she names a price for her company — knowing it is a mistake, doing it anyway — is the most honest moment in a film otherwise devoted to evasion, and it lands accordingly.\n\nFaye Wong as the hotelier\'s daughter carries the film\'s other emotional spine. Her subplot, in which she waits for letters from a man in Tokyo who replies slowly and then not at all, distills something about love and waiting and the peculiar cruelty of time that the film reaches for elsewhere with less success. The pairing of her scenes with Takuya Kimura, who plays the Japanese suitor with a quality of tender unavailability, generates the kind of feeling that the Chow Mo-wan sections increasingly cannot, because Chow has become something the film treats as inevitable: a man so devoted to mourning that he has made a lifestyle of it.\n\nThis is where 2046 earns its honest critique. Tony Leung does precisely what is asked of him — the performance is controlled, internally complex, physically inhabited — but Wong has written Chow into a corner from which no exit is possible or sought. As protagonist, Chow is a black hole. The women around him are vivid; he reflects them back dimmed. The film knows this — it is arguably the subject — but knowingness does not solve the problem of spending two hours with a character who has decided, in advance, that nothing will change him.\n\nChristopher Doyle and Kwan Pung-Leung share cinematography, and their work is among the most physically gorgeous Wong has ever achieved. The 1960s Hong Kong corridors are amber and close; the Singapore nights are thick with neon and rain; the sci-fi train is sleek and cold. William Chang\'s editing moves through time in the distinctive Wong manner — non-sequentially, by emotional association — and the film\'s fragmented structure mirrors its subject without overwhelming it. Shigeru Umebayashi\'s waltz returns once more, and once more it works, because the music has earned its resonance across two prior films and simply has to sound to do its job.\n\nAt its best, 2046 is among the most beautiful films of its decade. At its worst, it mistakes accumulation for depth, circling without closing. What saves it from the latter verdict is that the accumulation is not random — each woman, each failed connection, each slow train adds to a portrait of a person who has built an entire architecture of behavior to avoid confronting a single fact about himself. The film is the architecture. Whether the portrait justifies the scale is a question that will depend on the viewer. Those who find Chow\'s particular brand of romantic paralysis fascinating will find this inexhaustible. Those who need their subjects to move will run short of patience somewhere in the second hour."
    }
