    criticRating: "Exceptional",
    review: {
      themes: ["inheritance", "mortality", "complicity", "caregiving", "legacy", "guilt", "estrangement", "sacrifice"],
      mood: ["tender", "elegiac", "wrenching"],
      fullReview: "How to Make Millions Before Grandma Dies arrives at its subject through the back door of a small moral crime. M, a university dropout who has run out of both money and excuses, watches his cousin receive a substantial windfall after nursing their grandfather to the end. The arithmetic is obvious. Their grandmother Amah — Sino-Thai, older, recently diagnosed with terminal cancer — is next. M volunteers to move in, to cook, to accompany her to chemotherapy. He keeps a running tally in his head. The audience watches this and squirms, not because M is monstrous, but because his logic is uncomfortably legible.\n\nWhat director Pat Boonnitipat understands — and what makes the film work as well as it does — is that M\'s mercenary motivation does not need to be punished or quickly redeemed. It needs to be complicated. Over 126 minutes, the transactional framework through which M views his grandmother slowly corrodes, not through a single revelation but through the accumulation of small, unguardable moments: a habit she has, a story she tells, the way she moves through her kitchen, the way she speaks to the regulars at her fried fish stall. The film does not manufacture a turning point. It simply allows time to do what time does.\n\nUsha Seamkhum\'s performance as Amah is what holds the film\'s emotional architecture together. She plays a woman who has been the gravitational center of her family for decades — the kind of matriarch around whom others orbit, sometimes lovingly and sometimes resentfully — and who faces her own death with a mixture of humor, stubbornness, and a deeply private grief she never fully shows. Seamkhum gives Amah a dignity that is never sentimental and a warmth that never curdles into preciousness. It is a remarkable piece of work by an actress who deserves far wider recognition.\n\nPutthipong Assaratanakul, cast against the grain of his idol-pop-star image, is equally good at the more difficult task of making M\'s ambivalence feel honest. The film needs its audience to hold two truths simultaneously: that M came for the money, and that his love, when it arrives, is real. Assaratanakul manages this without ever letting the performance tip into either easy villainy or easy redemption. He holds the character\'s interior unresolved for longer than is comfortable, and the film is better for it.\n\nThe screenplay by Boonnitipat and Thodsapon Thiptinnakorn is shrewder than its premise initially suggests. The inheritance plot — which might seem like a narrative gimmick — is actually the film\'s moral engine, driving every family relationship and every scene of caregiving toward questions about what people owe each other and what love looks like when it is mixed up with calculation. The extended family orbiting Amah\'s diminishing health, each member with their own complicated stake in her legacy, gives the film a social texture that keeps it from collapsing into a simple two-hander and roots the personal story in the specific dynamics of Teochew Chinese-Thai family life.\n\nThat cultural specificity is one of the film\'s genuine strengths. The food, the ancestor rituals, the burial plot subplot, the mix of Thai and Teochew spoken between certain characters — these are not decorative cultural signifiers but load-bearing elements of the story. Amah\'s world is the product of a very particular history, and the film honors that without turning it into a museum exhibit. For viewers unfamiliar with the Sino-Thai community, the texture is revelatory. For those who recognize it, the film will feel like being handed something back.\n\nWhere the film occasionally stumbles is in its score, which sometimes arrives ahead of the scene to instruct the audience on what to feel rather than trusting what Seamkhum and Assaratanakul are already doing in front of the camera. There are a handful of passages — mostly in the final stretch — where emotional pressure is applied from outside the drama rather than generated from within it, and the film loses some of its hard-won restraint in those moments. They are not fatal flaws, but they are intrusions on a film that otherwise earns its emotion at full cost.\n\nPat Boonnitipat\'s direction is assured throughout. Cinematographer Boonyanuch Kraithong gives the film a warm, natural visual texture well-suited to its domestic scale — nothing ostentatious, everything in service of the people onscreen. The pacing is deliberate without becoming sluggish, each scene allowed to run a beat longer than strict narrative efficiency would require, which is exactly right for a story about learning to pay attention to someone before it is too late.\n\nThis is not a film that announces itself loudly or strains for importance. It tells a human story with precision and genuine care, and trusts that precision and care are enough. For anyone who has watched someone diminish, or has complicated their own capacity for love with their capacity for self-interest, or has tried to account for what they actually owe the people who made them — which is nearly everyone — it will find its way in."
    }
