    awards: [
      { body: "Amanda Awards (31st)", category: "Best Norwegian Film", result: "Won", year: 2022 },
      { body: "Amanda Awards (31st)", category: "Best Director", result: "Won", year: 2022 },
      { body: "Amanda Awards (31st)", category: "Best Screenplay", result: "Won", year: 2022 },
      { body: "Amanda Awards (31st)", category: "Best Cinematography", result: "Won", year: 2022 },
      { body: "European Film Awards (35th)", category: "Best Film", result: "Nominated", year: 2022 },
      { body: "European Film Awards (35th)", category: "Best Director", result: "Nominated", year: 2022 },
      { body: "European Film Awards (35th)", category: "Best Screenplay", result: "Nominated", year: 2022 },
      { body: "Cannes Film Festival (74th)", category: "Un Certain Regard — Official Selection", result: "Nominated", year: 2021 }
    ],
    criticRating: "Exceptional",
    review: {
      themes: ["cruelty", "innocence", "empathy", "amorality", "power", "childhood", "surveillance"],
      mood: ["disquieting", "bleak", "suffocating"],
      fullReview: "A family moves into a Norwegian housing estate at the start of summer. Ida, the older daughter, is frustrated by the constant demands of caring for her younger sister Anna, who is autistic and largely nonverbal. During the long Scandinavian days while their parents are occupied, Ida and Anna fall in with two other children from the estate: Ben, a quiet boy with a watchful quality that reads immediately as wrong, and Aisha, warm and perceptive in ways that seem to exceed ordinary empathy. Slowly, the four children discover they have developed abilities — telekinesis, a shared mental link, something closer to possession — and what they choose to do with these abilities, out of sight of every adult around them, is what the film is about.\n\nEskil Vogt, who wrote the screenplays for Joachim Trier\'s Oslo trilogy before directing his own features, has made a horror film that operates on a register most of the genre does not attempt. There are no monsters here except the ones that emerge from ordinary children when power arrives without conscience to govern it. The film\'s central proposition — that children are not innocent in the way adults prefer to believe, that the absence of moral formation is not neutrality but a void into which anything can move — is not new as a philosophical idea, but Vogt executes it with a specificity and patience that makes it feel newly disturbing.\n\nThe genius of the screenplay is structural: it gives each of the four children a distinct moral position and lets those positions collide. Ben is the film\'s engine, a child whose capacity for cruelty is established early and coldly, before the supernatural element arrives, and whose acquisition of power functions as the film\'s central horror. Aisha sits at the opposite pole — her ability is empathic, attuned to the suffering of others, and she registers what Ben is becoming before any adult can. Ida begins in a state of moral vacancy that is simply age-appropriate selfishness, and the film watches her gradually locate something like conscience. Anna, whose internal life has been inaccessible to everyone including her sister, finds in the psychic connection a language she has never had.\n\nAll four child performances are extraordinary in ways that defy easy explanation. Rakel Lenora Fløttum as Ida carries the moral weight of the film — hers is the consciousness that most closely tracks the audience\'s own shifting understanding — and she does it with the unguarded naturalism that only the best child direction can produce. Sam Ashraf as Ben is genuinely alarming: not because he performs menace but because he performs a specific kind of ordinary childish affect that has been hollowed out from the inside. Mina Yasmin Bremseth Asheim as Aisha brings a gravity that should be impossible at her age.\n\nSturla Brandth Grøvlen\'s cinematography — flat, overcast, the gray-green palette of a Nordic housing estate in perpetual summer twilight — gives the film its texture. Nothing is expressionistically lit or composed for atmosphere. The horror happens in the same light as the grocery runs and the playground equipment, and that ordinariness is the source of its power. Pessi Levanto\'s score uses strings and electronics in a way that works against the images rather than amplifying them: the music is there when the film is quiet, and conspicuously absent when violence erupts, which gives the violence a documentary quality that lingers.\n\nWhat the film refuses to do — and this is both its artistic integrity and the source of some frustration in viewers who wanted a cleaner moral shape — is to resolve the question of what childhood cruelty means or where it comes from. Ben is not explained. His home life is shown, briefly and without editorializing, and it is not sufficient explanation. Vogt is not interested in the sociology of how a child becomes this. He is interested in the fact that this child exists, and in what that requires the other children around him to become.\n\nThe Innocents is deeply uncomfortable to watch. It is also, for anyone willing to sit inside that discomfort, one of the more rigorously intelligent horror films made in recent years — a film that uses the genre not as a delivery mechanism for shock but as the precise instrument its subject requires."
    }
