    runtime: [
      { version: "Theatrical Cut", duration: "2:01" }
    ],
    awards: [
      { body: "Berlin International Film Festival (71st)", category: "Silver Bear Grand Jury Prize", result: "Won", year: 2021 }
    ],
    criticRating: "Exceptional",
    review: {
      themes: ["coincidence", "longing", "regret", "desire", "connection", "estrangement", "memory"],
      mood: ["tender", "wistful", "intimate"],
      fullReview: "Three stories. Three women. Three encounters with chance, each arriving at the kind of crossroads that most lives quietly contain but rarely acknowledge. In the first, a woman discovers that the man her best friend has fallen for is someone from her own past. In the second, a graduate student attempts to seduce a professor using a passage from his novel as bait, with consequences neither of them anticipated. In the third, two middle-aged women meet on a train and mistakenly believe they share a mutual acquaintance — and decide, briefly, to keep believing it anyway. Nothing here is plotted in the conventional sense. What Ryusuke Hamaguchi is after is something smaller and stranger: the way a single conversation, held long enough and honestly enough, can open a door that neither person knew was there.\n\nReleased in the same year as Drive My Car — which swept awards circuits worldwide and secured Hamaguchi an Academy Award — Wheel of Fortune and Fantasy is the quieter twin, the chamber piece to that film\'s symphony. It was shot quickly, on a modest budget, with minimal visual embellishment. There are no elaborate compositions, no score pushing emotional buttons, no camera movements designed to signal profundity. What there is instead is an almost radical faith in the face, the voice, and the pause. Hamaguchi places his actors in rooms together, points a camera at them, and lets conversation do what conversation actually does when two people stop performing for each other.\n\nThis sounds simple. It is not simple. It is in fact one of the more demanding creative visions operating in world cinema today, because it requires performers of unusual caliber and requires them to behave in ways that feel genuinely unguarded rather than rehearsed to appear unguarded. The cast here — largely unfamiliar outside Japan — meets the challenge entirely. Kotone Furukawa in the first segment brings a volatility to Meiko that keeps the audience perpetually uncertain whether she is about to do something reckless or something generous, and the ambiguity is the point. Kiyohiko Shibukawa as the embattled professor in the second segment does something rarer still: he plays a man caught between professional authority and personal vulnerability, and the moment the armor comes off is almost unbearably human. The third segment belongs to Fusako Urabe and Aoba Kawai, and it is the most formally daring of the three — a sustained act of mutual pretense that becomes, by its end, something unexpectedly moving.\n\nThe anthology structure is not a weakness. Each story is self-contained but they accumulate, building a composite portrait of what it means to be a person who carries their past alongside them, who encounters the present through the lens of what might have been. Hamaguchi is not interested in resolution. He is interested in the moment just before resolution might occur — the charged air of a conversation heading somewhere uncharted — and he has a gift for sustaining that tension without deflating it.\n\nThe title is the key. Fortune and fantasy: the randomness of circumstance, and the stories people tell themselves inside that randomness. Every segment turns on a misunderstanding, a gamble, a performance — and in each case the film asks whether the distinction between reality and invention matters as much as people tend to assume. The third story pushes this furthest: two strangers role-playing a relationship that never existed, and finding in the fiction something that the facts of their actual lives have not provided. It is the kind of ending that stays with a person not because it offers comfort but because it refuses to lie about what comfort sometimes costs.\n\nFor viewers coming to Hamaguchi through Drive My Car, this film offers a different angle on the same preoccupations — more compressed, more playful in its structure, and shot through with a lightness that the later film, for all its greatness, does not quite have. For anyone new to his work, it is the better starting point: a film that earns its emotional weight through precision rather than scale, and that makes the ordinary business of talking to another person feel, for two hours, like the most consequential thing in the world."
    }
