    review: {
      themes: ["class", "complicity", "desperation", "inheritance", "corruption", "survival", "coexistence"],
      mood: ["suffocating", "clinical", "bleak"],
      fullReview: "The film opens on silence. A woman sleeps in a large Moscow apartment, light changing slowly at the window. Her husband sleeps beside her, separated by the geometrical courtesy of a broad, expensive bed. Andrey Zvyagintsev holds this shot for longer than comfort allows, and in those first unhurried seconds he establishes exactly what kind of film Elena is going to be. Elena (Nadezhda Markina) is a former nurse who married money. Her husband Vladimir (Andrey Smirnov) is wealthy, older, and constitutionally unavailable in all the ways that never appear on paper. She cooks. She tends to him. She takes the metro across the city to visit her adult son Sergey (Aleksey Rozin), who lives in one of those Soviet-era housing blocks that look like the architectural equivalent of giving up — three children, no job, a wife who smokes through every frame, a teenage grandson whose education represents the only visible ladder out. When Vladimir survives a heart attack and subsequently decides how to distribute his estate, Elena is forced to act on a calculus she has been quietly running for years. Zvyagintsev is a filmmaker who treats moral catastrophe with the patience of a geologist. He doesn\'t hammer. He excavates. The screenplay, co-written with Oleg Negin, never once announces its intentions or editorializes its characters. Vladimir is not a villain. Elena is not a victim. The film watches both of them with the impartiality of a surveillance camera pointed at the exact intersection where class resentment and survival instinct collide, and it trusts the audience to feel the discomfort of not knowing who to side with. What Markina does with this role is one of the undervalued performances of the decade. She plays a woman who has long since finished the argument with herself and reached a conclusion — but plays her this way without ever signaling it, without a single moment of visible scheming or visible anguish. The horror of the performance is in its ordinariness. Elena moves through the film the way most people move through difficult decisions: by not quite looking at them directly. The audience watches her face for evidence of a crisis that the face simply refuses to show. Philip Glass contributes a score built on spare, cyclical phrases — the kind of music that doesn\'t resolve, that seems to continue past the point where the scene ends. It arrives infrequently enough that each entrance registers as something close to alarm. The placement is precise: the strings appear not at moments of action but at moments when the moral weight of something that has already happened begins to settle. Mikhail Krichman\'s cinematography does ideological work without the film ever acknowledging it. Vladimir\'s apartment is shot with clean wide angles, natural light, room to breathe. Sergey\'s housing block — when the film ventures across the class divide — is cramped, harshly lit, compositionally cluttered. The geography makes the argument. Two Russias, same city, essentially different planets, connected only by the woman who negotiates between them and pays a price only the audience fully tallies. Elena Lyadova\'s portrayal of Vladimir\'s estranged daughter Katerina deserves its own consideration. Katerina is the film\'s most uncomfortable presence precisely because she might be right. She is selfish — glitteringly, articulately selfish — but she is also lucid about what she and Vladimir share, about what Elena is, about what the marriage always was. Her contempt is delivered with such intelligence that it lands somewhere between insufferable and correct. Zvyagintsev doesn\'t let anyone off cleanly, and Katerina least of all, but he also refuses to let the audience dismiss her. The film premiered at Cannes in the Un Certain Regard section in May 2011, where it won the Jury Prize — a distinction that suited it well, since Elena is precisely the kind of cinema that resists easy categorization. It operates as a thriller where the tension is almost entirely moral rather than physical. It functions as a domestic drama that quietly indicts an entire social order. It is a crime film where the crime feels, from one angle, almost inevitable, and from another, entirely preventable, and from a third, already over before it begins. Where the film slightly hesitates is in its middle passages, where the patience tips occasionally into inertness, and where a few figures in the working-class milieu feel more like representatives of a thesis than fully inhabited people. These are forgivable shortcomings in a film this precisely assembled, but they register. What stays lodged after Elena — and the film does stay — is its final sequence: an image of continuation, of the world rearranging itself around an act the world knows nothing about, of ordinary life resuming with the serenity of something that has no idea what it is built upon. Zvyagintsev believes that ordinary people are fully capable of extraordinary moral compromise when pressed hard enough by desperation and contempt, and he refuses to judge them for it while making the audience feel the full weight of that refusal. That tension — between comprehending a character and knowing that comprehension changes nothing — is what separates Elena from the dozens of austere social dramas that mistake restraint for depth. The restraint here is earned. Every withheld emotion has somewhere to go, and the film knows exactly where."
    }
