    criticRating: "Exceptional",
    review: {
      themes: ["love", "injustice", "testimony", "race", "community", "family", "resistance", "time"],
      mood: ["tender", "luminous", "heartbreaking"],
      fullReview: "Clementine — Tish — Rivers is nineteen years old and pregnant, and the man she loves is in prison for a crime he did not commit. The film begins with this fact stated plainly, the way Baldwin always stated things plainly, and then it moves backward and forward through time, assembling the life of Tish and Alonzo Hunt — called Fonny — not as a case to be argued but as a love to be witnessed. The injustice at the center of the story is real and structural and named without euphemism. But Barry Jenkins is less interested in the machinery of that injustice than in what it costs, measured in the currency of two people who were building a life together.\n\nJames Baldwin published the novel in 1974, and its concerns — the weaponization of the American legal system against Black men, the way an entire community must reorganize itself around one act of institutional violence — have not dated in any way that could be called comfortable. Jenkins, adapting faithfully but not slavishly, finds the cinematic equivalent of Baldwin\'s first-person narration in a series of direct-to-camera addresses and a score by Nicholas Britell that functions less as accompaniment than as emotional weather. The film does not argue its politics. It lives inside them.\n\nJames Laxton\'s cinematography will divide viewers, and that division is worth taking seriously rather than dismissing. The frames are extraordinarily beautiful — candlelit, warm, composed with the kind of precision that announces itself. Some will find this beauty at odds with the material, a softening of what should be unsparing. The more defensible reading is that Jenkins is working in the tradition of Baldwin himself, who understood that beauty and tragedy are not opposites and that celebrating what is at risk is itself a political act. The film photographs its characters with love — saturated skin tones, close frames, unhurried attention — and this is not incidental to what it is saying about whose beauty has historically been deemed worthy of that attention.\n\nRegina King as Sharon Rivers — Tish\'s mother — carries the film\'s most formally demanding scenes, including a sequence set in Puerto Rico that ranks among the finest single scenes in American cinema of the last decade. What she is asked to do in that scene requires her to receive information, process it privately, and then perform something she does not feel, all in a single sustained take. She does this at a level that makes the surrounding craft temporarily invisible. The Academy Award she received for this performance was not a consolation prize.\n\nKiKi Layne and Stephan James hold the center of the film with a warmth that earns the film\'s romantic register without sentimentalizing it. Their Tish and Fonny are not idealized — they are young, occasionally uncertain, feeling their way toward a life — and this ordinariness is what makes what happens to them register as wrong in a visceral rather than merely intellectual way. Brian Tyree Henry appears in a single extended scene and uses it to deliver something quietly extraordinary: a portrait of what incarceration does to a man\'s relationship with his own body and his capacity for safety.\n\nColman Domingo as Tish\'s father gives the film its most fully inhabited adult male performance. His Joseph is a man who would do anything for his family and who has made a precise accounting of what that means in the world as it actually is. The warmth he brings to scenes that could easily tip into sentiment keeps the film anchored in something recognizably human.\n\nIf Beale Street Could Talk is not a perfect film. There are passages where the beauty becomes a kind of armor — where the loveliness of the image and the score creates distance precisely when proximity is most needed. The Puerto Rico sequence excepted, the film occasionally handles its most devastating material at a slight remove, as if afraid to go as far as its source permits. Baldwin\'s novel is not a beautiful object. Jenkins\' film sometimes is, and that distinction matters. It does not, however, undo what the film achieves: a full-throated insistence that this love was worth something, that the people caught inside this system were full human beings before they were victims of it, and that bearing witness is not a passive act."
    }
