    awards: [
      { body: "Independent Spirit Awards (34th)", category: "Best Feature", result: "Nominated", year: 2019 },
      { body: "Independent Spirit Awards (34th)", category: "Best Director", result: "Nominated", year: 2019 },
      { body: "Independent Spirit Awards (34th)", category: "Best Female Lead", result: "Nominated", year: 2019 },
      { body: "Independent Spirit Awards (34th)", category: "Best Male Lead", result: "Nominated", year: 2019 },
      { body: "Independent Spirit Awards (34th)", category: "Best Cinematography", result: "Nominated", year: 2019 }
    ],
    criticRating: "Exceptional",
    review: {
      themes: ["autonomy", "belonging", "sacrifice", "wilderness", "separation", "trauma", "compassion"],
      mood: ["tender", "sparse", "restless"],
      fullReview: "Will and his teenage daughter Tom live in a public forest outside Portland, hidden among the trees, leaving nothing behind them. They forage, they train, they stay quiet, and they have built between them a life of uncommon intimacy and mutual attentiveness. When they are discovered by park rangers and brought back into society — housed, assessed, enrolled in school, handed vegetables from community gardens — the question the film asks is not whether this life was legal or sustainable, but whether it was, in any real sense, wrong. Debra Granik holds that question open for the entire runtime without ever resolving it into a verdict, and that sustained moral patience is the film\'s most impressive achievement.\n\nGranik\'s previous fiction feature was Winter\'s Bone, the 2010 film that introduced Jennifer Lawrence to the world. The eight years between them apparently changed nothing about her fundamental instincts: she still shoots working-poor America with an eye that is documentary-precise without being anthropological, still finds in marginalized American landscapes a particular quality of green and grey that makes the familiar look newly inhabited. Michael McDonough\'s cinematography here — the Pacific Northwest rendered in muted, rain-softened light — is not scenic in the way that forest films tend to be scenic. It is material. The woods are something to be read, navigated, and slept in, not admired from a distance.\n\nWhat is extraordinary about Thomasin McKenzie in the role of Tom is how little she seems to be performing. She was sixteen during production, and carries the role with an equanimity that is neither precocious nor implausible — a teenager who has grown up outside the structures that produce most teenage behavior, and who meets the ordinary world, when it arrives, with the specific combination of curiosity and wariness that such an upbringing would produce. The film belongs to her, even if it takes a while to understand that. Ben Foster, as Will, is doing something more fragile and more difficult: a man who loves his daughter with total sincerity while being genuinely unable to give her what she needs, whose condition — the film handles this with notable restraint, never labeling it — was made elsewhere and cannot be unmade by love alone. His performance sits in a register of barely contained internal pressure that could have tipped toward sympathy-seeking at any moment and never does.\n\nThe screenplay, adapted by Granik and producer Anne Rosellini from Peter Rock\'s novel My Abandonment, is built entirely from small decisions. There are no confrontations that announce themselves as turning points, no scenes where anyone says the defining thing. The drama accumulates in refusals, in glances across rooms that contain too much history to articulate, in the particular way Tom looks at a beehive or a kitchen or a stranger who treats her with uncomplicated kindness. The film trusts that accumulation to do the work, and it does.\n\nOne of the things Leave No Trace quietly insists upon is that the communities Will and Tom pass through — the veterans\' housing, the Christmas tree farm, the off-grid settlement in the hills — are not judgments on their life choices but genuine alternatives. The people who help them are not fixed, comfortable, or certain. They are themselves navigating versions of the same question: how to live, and with whom, and at what cost to other parts of yourself. Dale Dickey, in a small role as a woman on the Christmas farm, handles this with characteristic directness. She is kind in a way that communicates experience rather than disposition, and her scenes with both Foster and McKenzie are among the film\'s most precisely observed.\n\nThe film\'s ending has been described as ambiguous, and technically that is accurate. But ambiguity implies equal weight to multiple outcomes, and Leave No Trace is not ambiguous — it is clear about what is happening and about who has arrived at something while someone else has not. That the film does not editorialize about this, does not soften or condemn, does not locate the tragedy in any one person\'s failure, is the mark of a filmmaker operating with real conviction.\n\nThis is one of the finest American films of the past decade, and one of the quietest."
    }
