    criticRating: "Great",
    review: {
      themes: ["mortality", "transience", "predation", "performance", "fate", "loneliness", "storytelling", "exploitation"],
      mood: ["wry", "elegiac", "morbid"],
      fullReview: "Six tales of the American West, presented as pages turning in an illustrated storybook. A singing gunslinger dispatches enemies with cheerful efficiency before meeting his own cosmically comic end. A would-be bank robber cannot catch a break from the rope. A limbless man declaims Shakespeare to prairie crowds while his keeper calculates the arithmetic of his usefulness. A grizzled prospector communes with a canyon as though it were a living thing. A woman traveling west toward a future she did not choose encounters something that changes everything. And five strangers share a coach ride whose destination, it gradually becomes clear, is not quite on any map.\n\nThe Coen Brothers have spent four decades building a body of work in which death arrives sideways — comic, abrupt, unearned, indifferent to whoever it takes. The Ballad of Buster Scruggs is the purest distillation of that sensibility they have yet assembled, freed from the obligations of a single narrative to roam across six different registers of the same obsession. What unites the segments is not theme exactly, or tone — the opening segment is practically a cartoon, while the closing one is a slow-creeping dread piece — but a conviction that the West, as a setting and as a mythology, has always been a story about how quickly a person can become a corpse.\n\nThe first two segments operate in the key of the absurd. Tim Blake Nelson plays Buster Scruggs as a self-narrating legend, all white hat and impossible marksmanship, singing his way through a world that cannot contain him. The comedy is broad and pointed: the film is already interrogating the genre\'s relationship to casual brutality before it has properly begun. James Franco, in the second chapter, brings a hangdog quality to a cowboy who cannot stay off the gallows, and the segment finds genuine laughs in the machinery of frontier justice without quite letting anyone off the moral hook.\n\nThe anthology\'s center of gravity is the third story, and it is where the film locates its sharpest thing to say. Harry Melling plays the limbless orator — a man who exists only as a torso and a voice, touring the territory performing Shakespeare and the Gettysburg Address for whoever will watch. Liam Neeson is his handler, a man of no evident cruelty who is simply running a business. The segment has almost no dialogue between them. It does not need it. The calculation Neeson\'s character makes, when he makes it, is legible in a single held shot. Melling, working without limbs and with nothing but his face and his considerable vocal instrument, delivers something that lingers well past the film\'s end — a portrait of a person whose entire value to the world is their ability to produce a performance, and what happens when that value is exceeded by something cheaper.\n\nTom Waits, in the fourth segment, does exactly what Tom Waits has always suggested he could do in a film if someone simply let him: carry a whole story on his shoulders through the sheer force of his presence. His gold prospector talks to the land, curses at the land, makes love to the land in his way, and the segment moves with the unhurried patience of a man who has nowhere else to be. Bruno Delbonnel\'s cinematography here achieves something genuinely beautiful — the canyon lit with a quality of light that feels found rather than manufactured.\n\nThe penultimate story, built around Zoe Kazan as a woman traveling west under her brother\'s reluctant care, is the film\'s most emotionally inhabited piece. Bill Heck plays a wagon train scout whose courtship of her is conducted across brief, honest exchanges while the convoy moves through landscape that dwarfs everyone. The story earns its emotion precisely by not telegraphing where it is going, and Kazan makes Alice Longabaugh\'s interior life vivid in the spaces between lines.\n\nThe final segment — five strangers in a coach after dark — is where the anthology completes its tonal journey from slapstick to something genuinely unnerving. Brendan Gleeson and Jonjo O\'Neill do the heavy lifting, and the segment builds its dread through conversation alone, letting the audience arrive at the destination slightly before the characters do.\n\nNot all six segments are equally strong. The second, Near Algodones, feels slight against what surrounds it — a punchline looking for a joke it never quite finds. And the anthology format, by design, prevents any single thread from accumulating the weight a feature-length commitment would allow. These are limitations the Coens accept rather than disguise, and most of the time the tradeoff is worth it: the range of tonal possibility across two hours is something a conventional narrative simply could not achieve.\n\nWhat the film ultimately argues — if argument is the right word for something this epigrammatic — is that the West was always a place where people went to die interestingly, and that the stories told about it have always been, at bottom, stories about that. The storybook framing announces this from the first frame. Every page that turns is one fewer page remaining."
    }
