    awards: [
      { body: "Academy Awards (73rd)", category: "Best Actress in a Leading Role", result: "Nominated", year: 2001 },
      { body: "Independent Spirit Awards (16th)", category: "Best Female Lead", result: "Nominated", year: 2001 },
      { body: "Independent Spirit Awards (16th)", category: "Best Director", result: "Nominated", year: 2001 },
      { body: "Independent Spirit Awards (16th)", category: "Best Cinematography", result: "Nominated", year: 2001 },
      { body: "Satellite Awards (4th)", category: "Best Actress in a Motion Picture Drama", result: "Nominated", year: 2000 },
      { body: "Satellite Awards (4th)", category: "Best Director", result: "Nominated", year: 2000 },
      { body: "Critics Choice Awards (6th)", category: "Best Actress", result: "Nominated", year: 2001 }
    ],
    criticRating: "Exceptional",
    review: {
      themes: ["addiction", "delusion", "degradation", "loneliness", "consumption", "despair", "fantasy"],
      mood: ["suffocating", "harrowing", "corrosive"],
      fullReview: "Four people in Coney Island, Brooklyn, each with a dream they cannot quite hold. Sara Goldfarb, a widow alone in her apartment, receives a phone call telling her she may appear on a television program — and begins starving herself to fit a red dress she once wore, medicating the process with diet pills her doctor prescribes with spectacular irresponsibility. Her son Harry and his girlfriend Marion want money enough to fund a fashion boutique; they sell heroin to fund their own habit. Harry\'s friend Tyrone, who carries the memory of his mother as the one pure thing, is pulled deeper into a supply chain that has no interest in keeping him alive. By summer\'s end, all four are in freefall. By winter, the film has done things to them that cannot be undone.\n\nDarren Aronofsky structures the film in three titled movements — Summer, Fall, Winter — and the temperature of each section is literal. Summer pulses and sweats; the editing is percussive, the colours warm and oversaturated. Fall begins the contraction. By Winter, the film is cold and institutional and moving toward endings that it does not flinch from showing. Matthew Libatique\'s cinematography shifts with the seasons in ways that feel physiologically accurate: the world genuinely looks different when a person is well-fed and hopeful versus when they are sick and cornered, and Libatique and Aronofsky understand this at a cellular level.\n\nThe film\'s formal ambitions are real and mostly earned. The split-screen sequences, the extreme close-ups of pupils dilating and pills dissolving and refrigerators lurching open, the rapid-fire montage that compresses the ritual of use into a percussive thirty-second sequence — these are not MTV gestures. They are the film\'s argument rendered visually: addiction is repetition, is rhythm, is a body learning the same terrible lesson over and over while something essential in the person keeps insisting it will be different this time. Clint Mansell\'s score, performed by the Kronos Quartet, is one of the most effective in American cinema of this era — the central theme returns in varied forms as the film progresses, each iteration a little more frayed, a little more desperate, until the final movement becomes something close to unbearable.\n\nEllen Burstyn\'s performance as Sara is the reason the film matters beyond its formal accomplishments. What she does in this role — the specific quality of Sara\'s loneliness, the way her face opens when the television screen lights up, the particular brightness that diet pills lend her and then strip away — constitutes one of the finest pieces of screen acting in recent decades. The character could have been grotesque, a cautionary figure, but Burstyn insists on her full humanity throughout, even as the film systematically dismantles what remains of Sara\'s hold on herself. The Academy nominated her and, in one of the institution\'s more inexplicable decisions, gave the award to someone else.\n\nJared Leto and Jennifer Connelly carry the weight of their characters through the film\'s more schematic middle sections with genuine commitment, though the screenplay — adapted by Aronofsky and Selby from Selby\'s 1978 novel — gives Marion in particular fewer interior scenes than the role demands. She remains somewhat opaque where Sara is transparent, which makes the trajectory of her storyline more shocking than it is devastating. Marlon Wayans, in a dramatic departure from everything his career had been to that point, handles Tyrone with quiet dignity. His storyline\'s final movement — stranded in the American South, far from everyone who knew him before any of this happened — is the film\'s most politically charged passage, and the one it treats with the least elaboration.\n\nThe film is not without its problems. Aronofsky\'s unwillingness to look away from suffering tips occasionally into the pornographic, particularly in the final sequences where accumulation and spectacle begin to converge. There is a version of the argument that says this is precisely the point — that the film wants the audience to feel implicated in the voyeurism — but a counterargument exists: that relentlessness without modulation eventually numbs rather than deepens. The film\'s third act is so precisely engineered for maximum impact that it occasionally feels engineered, the tragedy slightly mechanical in its completeness.\n\nNone of which is enough to diminish what Requiem for a Dream actually achieves. It is the rare film that makes addiction legible — not as moral failure, not as weakness, but as a process with its own internal logic and its own terrible momentum. Every character in it is pursuing something that once felt like happiness. The film\'s real subject is the distance between what people dream and what they get, and how that distance, left unexamined, becomes the very substance of a life. Viewers who can tolerate what it puts them through will find it impossible to forget."
    }
