    criticRating: "Masterpiece",
    review: {
      themes: ["memory", "abandonment", "class", "womanhood", "grief", "loyalty", "invisibility"],
      mood: ["elegiac", "intimate", "devastating"],
      fullReview: "Roma is set in the Colonia Roma neighborhood of Mexico City, 1970 and 1971. Cleo, a young indigenous domestic worker from Oaxaca, moves through the rhythms of a middle-class household — waking early, cleaning the car-fouled courtyard, shepherding four children to school, preparing meals, folding laundry. The family she serves is intact on the surface and quietly fracturing underneath. Over the course of a year, both Cleo and her employer Sofía will be abandoned by the men in their lives, and the film watches what that does to two women who are bound together by labor, affection, and an enormous gulf of class that neither the screenplay nor the camera ever allows the audience to forget.\n\nAlfonso Cuarón shot this film himself, in black and white, in 65mm, and the results are almost unreasonably beautiful — not in the prettified way that tends to hollow out period films, but with a kind of empirical tenderness, as if the camera were trying to memorize rather than aestheticize. The wide compositions are famous by now: a dog trotting across a courtyard, an airplane passing in a strip of sky above the roofline, a horizon of burning grassland during a New Year\'s gathering in the country. Cuarón holds each frame long enough that the image accumulates meaning, and the slow panning movements within scenes create a sense of life observed rather than constructed. The film never announces what it wants an audience to feel. It simply shows, with great patience, and waits.\n\nYalitza Aparicio, in her first film role — her first acting experience of any kind — carries the entire weight of the picture with a stillness that defies category. Cleo is not a passive character despite the passivity of her circumstances. Every small decision she makes, every moment of hesitation or quiet care, communicates an inner life that is fully present even when the world around her treats her as furniture. The scene in which she receives a devastating piece of news in a doctor\'s office and is immediately asked to keep working is one of the most quietly shattering pieces of screen acting in recent memory. Aparicio does almost nothing and it is unbearable.\n\nMarina de Tavira, as Sofía, is given far more dialogue and uses every line precisely. Her character could easily have been rendered as a foil or a contrast — the privileged woman whose grief is somehow lesser than the servant\'s — but Cuarón refuses that simplicity. Sofía\'s pain is real and her limitations are real, and the film asks audiences to hold both simultaneously without resolving them into a hierarchy.\n\nThe political backdrop of the Corpus Christi massacre of 1971 enters the film at a specific and formally devastating moment, without being announced or explained. This is characteristic of how Roma handles history: it does not frame events for the audience, it allows them to arrive the way they arrive in life — without warning, without context, as sudden ruptures in the fabric of the ordinary. The effect is disorienting in exactly the right way. It forces viewers to locate themselves in the experience rather than observe it from a safe editorial distance.\n\nSome critics have raised the question of whether Cuarón, a man of the class being served in this film, can fully reckon with what Cleo\'s life costs her. It is a serious question and it does not have a clean answer. What can be said is that the film is visibly aware of the question — that the camera\'s gaze carries its own complicity, that the beauty of the compositions is also a form of aestheticization that Cleo herself would never have experienced. Whether that awareness is sufficient is something each viewer will need to decide. The discomfort it generates is, in this writer\'s view, part of the film\'s honesty rather than evidence of its failure.\n\nRoma works at a frequency that does not suit every viewer. Nothing explodes. The dramatic events — and there are several, each more punishing than the last — arrive quietly and are processed quietly. For audiences accustomed to films that signal their emotional moments with swell music and close-ups, this restraint can read as coldness. It is not coldness. It is the opposite of coldness. It is the film insisting that grief and love and endurance do not require orchestration to be real. The ocean sequence near the end, which is among the most viscerally frightening things Cuarón has ever shot, works precisely because the film has spent two hours teaching the audience to pay attention to bodies in space without cinematic amplification. By that point, the stakes are felt in the stomach.\n\nThis is a film made from memory — Cuarón has said as much, and the specificity of the detail confirms it — and memory is the register in which it ultimately operates. Not nostalgia, which is memory processed into comfort, but the rawer thing: the sensation of a moment that cannot be recovered, held in the image just long enough to feel its loss."
    }
