    criticRating: "Masterpiece",
    review: {
      themes: ["class", "deception", "resentment", "aspiration", "complicity", "privilege", "performance"],
      mood: ["corrosive", "electric", "unsettling"],
      fullReview: "The Kim family lives in a cramped semi-basement apartment in Seoul — the kind of unit where the windows sit at pavement level and passing ankles are the closest thing to a view. They fold pizza boxes for minimum wage, steal WiFi from a neighbor who has not yet set a password, and discuss their circumstances with the dark humor of people who have not yet given up. When the son Ki-woo lands a tutoring job at the wealthy Park household through a forged credential, the Kims begin to sense an opening. What follows is a comedy of incremental infiltration — one family member inserted into the Park household, then another, then another — executed with the precision of a heist film and the wit of something far more dangerous.\n\nBong Joon Ho has spent his career working in genre while systematically refusing to be contained by it. Parasite is the fullest expression of that instinct: it is a comedy until it isn\'t, a thriller before it becomes something else entirely, a social satire whose teeth get sharper the longer it runs. The screenplay, co-written with Han Jin-won, is constructed with the exactness of a mechanism — every detail placed to be retrieved later, every joke carrying a secondary meaning, every comfortable assumption positioned to be pulled out from under the audience. The film earns its reputation for rewatchability because it is almost impossible to see on a first viewing what Bong is actually doing with the material.\n\nThe spatial architecture does most of the film\'s political work. The semi-basement apartment where the Kims live is not quite underground — they can see out, but only barely. The Park house is all clean lines and expensive light, designed by a famous architect, built on a hill above the noise of the city. The distance between these two spaces is measured in the film through smell, through the direction water flows during a storm, through who gets to sit in the garden and who maintains it. Bong does not hide the metaphor. He builds it into every wall and staircase and asks the audience to sit inside it for two hours.\n\nSong Kang-ho, playing the Kim patriarch Ki-taek, is one of those actors who does more with stillness than most do with a monologue. There is a moment — mid-film, in the wake of a particular humiliation suffered within earshot of the wrong people — where he simply sits, and the camera holds on him long enough that a specific understanding settles over the audience. The screenplay will eventually find words for what he is thinking. They will arrive at the end, and they will land hard.\n\nThe Parks resist easy reading, which is part of what makes the film so honest. Cho Yeo-jeong plays the wife Yeon-kyo with a particular kind of obliviousness — not cruelty, but the effortless incuriosity of a woman who has never needed to think too carefully about the people who move through her house. Lee Sun-kyun gives the husband a similar quality: a man who considers himself decent, and probably is, within the narrow terms his position has established for decency. The film is concerned with precisely this gap — between deliberate harm and structural harm, between active contempt and passive indifference — and it refuses to let either family off the hook.\n\nThe tonal rupture the film engineers in its second half has been discussed so extensively it has become part of the film\'s mythology. What is worth noting is that Bong does not treat it as a break from what came before. The darkness was always encoded in the architecture and the economics, present from the opening frames, waiting for the precise conditions required to surface. When it does, the comedy does not disappear. It curdles.\n\nJung Jae-il\'s score works in close consultation with the cutting rhythm, and Hong Kyung-pyo\'s cinematography makes the Park house feel simultaneously aspirational and faintly sinister — all that horizontal space and natural light functioning less like a home than like a display of someone\'s self-concept. The production design by Lee Ha-jun is among the most thematically loaded in recent Korean cinema, where the physical geography of every room carries information about who is permitted to feel at ease within it.\n\nParasite became the first non-English language film to win the Academy Award for Best Picture, a fact that received enormous attention. The film neither needed that validation nor is diminished by it. What it is, stripped of the awards cycle and the historical footnote, is a film made by someone in complete command of every available tool, at the peak of their powers, saying something clear and corrosive and true about how the world is organized and who it was organized to serve. The semi-basement window is the film\'s controlling image — close enough to see the street, too low to be seen as anyone worth looking at."
    }
