    criticRating: "Masterpiece",
    review: {
      themes: ["ecology", "industrialization", "coexistence", "war", "sacrifice", "corruption", "balance"],
      mood: ["epic", "elegiac", "haunting"],
      fullReview: "Set in the Muromachi period of feudal Japan, the film follows Ashitaka, a young prince who receives a curse from a dying demon boar and travels west seeking a cure. What he finds is a conflict that has been building for centuries: the iron-smelting settlement of Irontown, run by the formidable Lady Eboshi, is clearing ancient forest to feed its furnaces. The forest gods, led by a wolf clan that has adopted a human girl named San, are fighting back. Ashitaka arrives not as a savior but as a witness — someone trying to see clearly when everyone around him has already chosen a side.\n\nThe word that keeps returning when watching Princess Mononoke is seriousness. Hayao Miyazaki made this film without a single throwaway moment. There are no sidekick comedics, no villain monologues, no clean moral victories. The script holds an almost prosecutorial patience with complexity, insisting that every party in this conflict has a comprehensible claim on the land. Eboshi is building a place where lepers and brothel workers — people discarded by samurai society — can live with dignity. She is also destroying something irreplaceable. The film refuses to resolve this into condemnation. It watches, instead, with something like grief.\n\nJoe Hisaishi\'s score operates at the scale of the imagery: vast, ceremonial, built on leitmotifs that return transformed rather than merely repeated. The music does not signal emotions so much as inhabit the same register as the film itself — a register of things too large and too old to be easily contained. Miyazaki and his animation teams render the ancient forest as a genuinely sacred space, not through sentimentality but through visual specificity: the kodama rattling in the canopy, the way light moves through moss so old it seems geological, the Great Forest Spirit that is simultaneously a deer and something else entirely, something that does not have a frame of reference in the natural world.\n\nThe violence is the element that most consistently surprises viewers expecting the gentler register of My Neighbor Totoro. Limbs are severed. Heads roll. A boar god dissolves into writhing tentacles of curse. None of this is gratuitous — it is the honest consequence of a film set in a world where human beings and ancient gods are in direct physical conflict — but it lands with force because Miyazaki has not prepared anyone for cushioning. Pain in this film costs something.\n\nYuriko Ishida\'s vocal performance as San carries the film\'s most difficult emotional register: a human being who has completely rejected her humanity, raised by wolves, existing in a kind of furious grief at what her species has done. The relationship between San and Ashitaka — who is drawn to her without understanding why, who she cannot fully hate without understanding why — is the quiet miracle at the center of all the spectacle. It is not a romance that resolves. It is two people who recognize each other across a divide that will not close, and choose to carry that recognition anyway.\n\nWhat distinguishes Princess Mononoke from every other ecological narrative in cinema is that it does not offer a solution. Irontown is not destroyed. The forest is not restored. The film ends somewhere closer to exhausted truce than triumph, with the understanding that humans and nature will continue to need each other and continue to damage each other, and that the most anyone can do is try to see clearly through their own moment of the conflict. Thirty years on, that refusal to simplify feels less like a limitation and more like the most adult thing the film could have done. Some problems are not solved. Some films are honest enough to say so."
    }
