    criticRating: "Exceptional",
    review: {
      themes: ["memory", "selfdeception", "identity", "revenge", "manipulation", "unreliability", "grief"],
      mood: ["disorienting", "tense", "cerebral"],
      fullReview: "Leonard Shelby cannot form new memories. Since a violent attack that killed his wife and left him with anterograde amnesia, he has been unable to retain anything beyond the last quarter-hour. He wakes each morning with no knowledge of where he is, what he has done, or who the people around him are. What he does have are Polaroids with notes written on them, a system of classified facts tattooed in reverse across his body, and a mission: find and kill the man who murdered his wife. Memento — Christopher Nolan\'s second feature, made on a fraction of the budget that would define the rest of his career — turns this premise into something formally audacious and philosophically unsettling.\n\nThe film runs backwards. Not literally reversed, but structured in reverse chronology: each scene ends where the previous one began, so the audience is always arriving somewhere Leonard has already been, knowing no more than he does about how things got to this point. Intercut with these reverse sequences is a second thread — black and white, running chronologically forward — in which Leonard speaks to someone on the phone, working through a story about a man named Sammy Jankis who shared his condition. The two threads move toward each other until they meet, and what that meeting reveals is not a twist so much as a reckoning.\n\nThe structure is the argument. Nolan and his brother Jonathan — whose short story provided the source material — are not using the reverse chronology as a gimmick to generate suspense. They are using it to make the audience experience, in a controlled and deliberate way, what it actually means to operate without short-term memory. Every scene arrives stripped of context. Every character who appears is someone Leonard cannot vouch for. Every piece of information he holds could have been placed there by anyone with sufficient motivation. The film implicates the audience in Leonard\'s epistemological problem: we are, for most of its runtime, exactly as lost as he is.\n\nGuy Pearce carries the film on the narrowest of emotional registers, and it is exactly the right choice. Leonard is not a character who emotes — he cannot afford to, because emotion requires the continuity of experience to accumulate. What Pearce gives instead is a performance of sustained watchfulness: a man who has learned to read the present with hypervigilance because the present is all he ever has. It is an exhausting way to live, and Pearce makes it feel like that without ever editorializing. Joe Pantoliano, as the cheerful, evasive Teddy, does some of the finest work of his career in a role that requires him to be read differently each time he appears. Carrie-Anne Moss brings a cold precision to Natalie that reveals its full dimensions only in retrospect.\n\nWally Pfister\'s cinematography gives Southern California an appropriately bleached and anonymous quality — a world of motels, parking lots, and diners that could be anywhere, that resists becoming a place Leonard could orient himself within. David Julyan\'s score is one of the more underrated elements: ambient and slightly unmoored, it mirrors the film\'s refusal to let comfort settle in.\n\nWhere Memento earns the most serious consideration is in its central moral question, which it poses without melodrama and refuses to resolve cleanly. If memory is what makes us accountable — if a man cannot remember what he did yesterday, does yesterday still belong to him? — then what happens to guilt, to justice, to the very concept of a self that persists through time? Leonard has constructed a system to compensate for what he has lost. The film\'s darkest suggestion is that the system itself is the problem: that the notes and the tattoos and the Polaroids do not restore objectivity but instead harden whatever beliefs he carried into his condition, insulating them from correction.\n\nThe film is not without limitations. Its female characters exist almost entirely as functions of Leonard\'s investigation, and Moss in particular is given a character whose richness is structural rather than human. The emotional temperature is held at such a deliberate remove that some viewers will find the whole enterprise more impressive than moving — which is a fair response, though not an entirely damning one. A film does not have to generate warmth to generate genuine insight.\n\nWhat it does — and what very few films in the thriller category have managed before or since — is make its formal apparatus inseparable from its meaning. Strip away the structure and there is no film left, because the structure is what the film is about. That kind of total integration between form and content is rarer than it should be, and Nolan, who has since worked at a scale that precludes this kind of precision, has never quite pulled it off again."
    }
