    criticRating: "Exceptional",
    review: {
      themes: ["transience", "connection", "mortality", "longing", "idealism", "performance"],
      mood: ["tender", "wandering", "bittersweet"],
      fullReview: "Before Sunrise follows Jesse (Ethan Hawke), an American backpacker drifting through Europe, who meets Céline (Julie Delpy), a French student returning to Paris, on a train approaching Vienna. With a flight home departing the next morning and nothing but a city and a night between them, Jesse proposes something impulsive: get off the train together, wander until dawn, and see what happens. Céline agrees. What unfolds across those hours is one of cinema\'s most disarmingly honest portraits of human connection.\n\nRichard Linklater made this film for roughly two and a half million dollars in 1994, shooting on location through Vienna\'s streets, cafés, record shops, and cathedrals, and the geography does something essential: it refuses to be merely decorative. The city is alive and indifferent in equal measure, a backdrop that does not perform romance but quietly enables it. Jesse and Céline move through it like two people who understand — at some level below conscious thought — that the night itself is conspiring to make things feel significant.\n\nThe film\'s method is radical in its simplicity. Two people talk. They talk about death, about their families, about the possibility of souls, about the particular variety of loneliness that arrives even in company. The screenplay, written by Linklater and Kim Krizan, has an unusual quality: it feels simultaneously scripted and overheard. The conversations carry the rhythm of real thought, where sentences trail off and circle back, where a person changes their mind mid-speech. Long, unbroken takes demand genuine presence — from the actors and from whoever is watching.\n\nWhat makes this work is that neither character is especially profound. Jesse is a little too eager to sound wise; Céline tilts occasionally toward the romantic idealism of someone who has read the right books but has not yet been properly disappointed. These are not flaws in the writing — they are the writing. Linklater is making a film about the way young people perform intellectual intimacy when they sense it might become something more, and both Hawke and Delpy are sharp enough to honor that complexity without ever signaling to the audience that they know better than their characters.\n\nHawke in particular does something difficult. Jesse could easily become insufferable — a verbose American convinced his alienation is interesting. Instead Hawke plays him as genuinely searching, a little frightened underneath the confidence, and the gaps between his certainties are where the film finds its pulse. Delpy matches him moment for moment, bringing a sharpness to Céline that prevents the film from curdling into sentiment. When she pushes back on an idea of his, it does not feel like conflict — it feels like two people thinking in real time.\n\nLee Daniel\'s cinematography keeps things close and unhurried. There are long stretches where the camera simply follows these two people walking, and the framing never flatters them in a way that feels manufactured. This is a film allergic to the visual grammar of romance movies, even as it delivers one of cinema\'s most genuinely romantic experiences.\n\nWhat stays with a person after watching is not any single scene but the accumulation of small moments: a game invented with a payphone, a record booth that becomes a confessional of sorts, and the way the film handles time in its final act with a quiet brutality that hits harder than any melodrama could. Linklater understands something that directors twice his experience sometimes miss — that restraint is its own kind of power, and that the most devastating beats are often the ones the camera does not linger on.\n\nThe film has flaws. Some passages of dialogue strain toward the literary, where a character produces something too tidy and considered for the circumstances — a sentence that belongs in a notebook rather than a conversation. These are small interruptions in something that is, overall, a genuine achievement.\n\nBefore Sunrise is the kind of film that arrives differently depending on when a person first encounters it. Seen at twenty, it feels like prophecy. Seen at forty, it functions more like a letter from a self that no longer exists. Both readings are correct. That is the mark of a film that has found something real and held onto it."
    }
