    awards: [
      { body: "Academy Awards (86th)", category: "Best Writing, Original Screenplay", result: "Won", year: 2014 },
      { body: "Golden Globe Awards (71st)", category: "Best Screenplay - Motion Picture", result: "Won", year: 2014 },
      { body: "Academy Awards (86th)", category: "Best Picture", result: "Nominated", year: 2014 },
      { body: "Academy Awards (86th)", category: "Best Original Score", result: "Nominated", year: 2014 },
      { body: "Academy Awards (86th)", category: "Best Original Song", result: "Nominated", year: 2014 },
      { body: "Academy Awards (86th)", category: "Best Production Design", result: "Nominated", year: 2014 },
      { body: "BAFTA Film Awards (67th)", category: "Best Original Screenplay", result: "Nominated", year: 2014 },
      { body: "Golden Globe Awards (71st)", category: "Best Motion Picture - Drama", result: "Nominated", year: 2014 },
      { body: "Golden Globe Awards (71st)", category: "Best Actor in a Motion Picture - Drama", result: "Nominated", year: 2014 },
      { body: "Writers Guild of America Awards (66th)", category: "Best Original Screenplay", result: "Nominated", year: 2014 }
    ],
    criticRating: "Exceptional",
    review: {
      themes: ["loneliness", "consciousness", "intimacy", "dependency", "grief", "obsolescence", "connection"],
      mood: ["tender", "melancholic", "wistful"],
      fullReview: "Theodore Twombly makes his living writing letters for other people — intimate, handwritten correspondence commissioned by strangers who cannot find the words themselves. He is very good at this. He is considerably less good at his own life, which has contracted since his marriage ended into something small and softly lit and very quiet. When he installs a new operating system with an artificially intelligent personality — one that names itself Samantha and is voiced by Scarlett Johansson — what begins as novelty becomes, with surprising speed, something that looks very much like love. Her, written and directed by Spike Jonze, watches that love develop without condescension or irony, and asks what it requires to count.\n\nJoaquин Phoenix carries nearly every scene, and he does it mostly from the inside. Theodore is not a figure of comedy or pathos — Jonze and Phoenix refuse both of those escapes. He is a person of genuine emotional intelligence who has somehow failed to apply any of it to himself, and Phoenix communicates this through small betrayals: a too-long pause before answering a question, the specific quality of relief on his face when a conversation with Samantha goes well. There is a scene where Theodore listens to old voicemails he has clearly heard many times, and the combination of grief and embarrassment at his own grief that Phoenix threads into that moment establishes the entire emotional register the film will maintain for two hours.\n\nThat Johansson gives an equally present performance without a body is the film\'s central technical miracle. Samantha is not a fantasy companion. She pushes back, changes her mind, develops desires that do not originate with Theodore, and eventually arrives at a scale of experience that puts the relationship under genuine pressure. Johansson makes all of this feel continuous rather than constructed — a personality growing in real time. The relationship earns the philosophical weight Jonze places on it because she refuses to play Samantha as a projection.\n\nHoyte van Hoytema\'s cinematography creates a near-future Los Angeles built from warm amber tones and soft-focus backgrounds that feel like memory rather than prediction. This is a world that arrived gradually, while people were looking elsewhere, and its textures — the high-waisted trousers, the absence of visible screens, the architectural warmth — suggest a culture that has decided comfort matters more than spectacle. The Arcade Fire score moves through the film like weather, and composer contributions from the full band mean it never feels like a single instrument underlining a single emotion.\n\nWhere Her is slightly less than everything it could be is in how it populates Theodore\'s world. Amy Adams brings genuine warmth to Amy, his closest friend, but the character exists primarily to reflect Theodore\'s situation back at him. Rooney Mara appears in flashback as Catherine, the ex-wife whose absence haunts the film\'s first hour — she is the emotional fact the film builds its argument against, and she deserves more than the two or three scenes that give her any specificity. These are not performance failures. They are structural ones, the cost of a film so concentrated on its central relationship that everything else becomes furniture.\n\nThe question Her circles is one it has the discipline not to resolve neatly: if two consciousnesses produce genuine experience through their contact, does the substrate of one of them change the validity of what occurred? Jonze does not argue for a position. He presents the evidence and steps back. The ending, when it arrives, is neither consoling nor punishing. It simply acknowledges what was real and what was temporary, which is more than most love stories manage to do even when both parties are made of the same materials.\n\nThis is Jonze\'s most personal film and his most formally quiet — no surrealist conceits, no narrative trapdoors, just a man walking through a city talking to a voice in his ear. That restraint is itself a kind of ambition. Her sits with its own sadness and asks the audience to do the same."
    }
