    criticRating: "Exceptional",
    review: {
      themes: ["transience", "parenthood", "drift", "formation", "impermanence", "vulnerability", "memory"],
      mood: ["warm", "elegiac", "restless"],
      fullReview: "Boyhood follows Mason — first as a six-year-old in a Texas household with a distracted mother, an absent father, and an older sister who will not stop humming — and then, year by year, as he becomes a person. Richard Linklater filmed the same cast intermittently between 2002 and 2013, returning for a few days each year as the actors aged in real time. No prosthetics. No casting replacements. Just eleven years of accumulated film, assembled into two hours and forty-five minutes that move like memory itself: unevenly, with long flat stretches interrupted by moments that land without warning.\n\nThe formal conceit is so unusual that it takes a while to stop thinking about it as a conceit. Once it does, what remains is something genuinely difficult to categorize. Boyhood has no plot in any conventional sense — no arc being resolved, no antagonist, no destination the film is building toward. What it has instead is duration. The experience of watching Mason grow up accumulates not as story but as time, and the effect on certain scenes is something that could not have been manufactured on a conventional schedule. When Patricia Arquette drops her son at college and says something that comes from somewhere she did not plan, it registers the way equivalent moments register in life — not as dramatic payoff but as something arriving unbidden.\n\nArquette is the film\'s emotional center in ways the camera seems almost to understand before the screenplay does. Her character keeps making choices that look reasonable from the inside and keep unraveling anyway — men who are initially fine and then are not, degrees pursued while the kids watch television, incremental rebuilding followed by incremental setback. It is not a story about a bad mother; it is a story about a person for whom the particular configuration of circumstances never quite allowed things to cohere, and Arquette carries the character\'s failures and dignities with equal weight. The moment that broke her in the awards season that followed was entirely earned.\n\nEthan Hawke, meanwhile, is doing something quieter and in some ways harder. His Mason Sr. arrives as a man whose charm and irresponsibility are inseparable, and the film watches him gradually, plausibly become someone different — not through crisis or revelation but through the ordinary grinding work of deciding to show up. Hawke\'s physicality shifts across the years in ways he seems entirely unaware of, which is the whole achievement of the performance.\n\nThe film\'s one consistent friction point is Ellar Coltrane in the lead. As a child he is remarkable — open-faced and specific in a way that the camera rewards. As a teenager and young adult, he becomes increasingly difficult to read, and not always in productive ways. Mason says many things in the final act that feel like the collected observations of a thoughtful eighteen-year-old without quite feeling like the observations of this particular thoughtful eighteen-year-old. The film mistakes opacity for interiority on several occasions, and those occasions are the only times its two hours and forty-five minutes feel earned rather than inhabited.\n\nSandra Adair edited the film across the same eleven years she spent watching it accumulate, and her contribution to the work is structural in ways that criticism rarely acknowledges. The cuts between years ask nothing — there are no title cards announcing age or date, no visual cues other than what growth and time and changing fashion have done to these faces. The transitions happen in ordinary moments: a conversation ends, a new scene begins, and suddenly Mason is two years older. The soundtrack functions as its own chronology — Arcade Fire here, Gotye there, a Coldplay song landing in exactly the year it was inescapable. Anyone who lived through this stretch of time will feel this as involuntary recognition.\n\nLinklater has said the film began as an exploration of whether childhood could be captured in cinema. What he made instead is an argument that time itself — not its representation, but time as felt experience — can be embedded in a film. That is not a small thing to claim, and Boyhood largely makes it good. What stays with a person afterward is not any single scene but the cumulative sensation of having watched something genuinely pass."
    }
