    criticRating: "Exceptional",
    review: {
      themes: ["nihilism", "belonging", "regret", "motherhood", "acceptance", "exhaustion", "sacrifice", "inheritance"],
      mood: ["frenetic", "tender", "anarchic"],
      fullReview: "Evelyn Wang runs a laundromat that is failing, a marriage that has gone quiet, and a relationship with her daughter Joy that is close to collapse. Her elderly father has just arrived from overseas with old opinions about how her life has been lived. The IRS wants receipts. The washing machines need fixing. And somewhere in the middle of a tax audit, the entire multiverse begins bleeding through the walls. Everything Everywhere All at Once is the film that the Daniels — Daniel Kwan and Daniel Scheinert — spent years building toward, and what they have made is, improbably, one of the most emotionally coherent films to come out of American cinema in years. The chaos is not incidental. It is the point.\n\nThe film operates at a speed that borders on aggression. Paul Rogers\'s editing is the kind that film school classes will study for decades — not because it is technically flashy, but because every cut is doing real work. The multiverse-jumping is dizzyingly frequent, and the film never stops to explain itself for very long, which is the correct choice. Audiences are trusted to keep up, and keeping up is rewarded. What starts as disorienting becomes, by the end of the second act, fluent. The grammar of the film teaches itself as it goes.\n\nMichelle Yeoh carries the weight of all of it. Evelyn is not an easy character to hold — she is selfish and warm, dismissive and desperate, capable of extraordinary heroism and ordinary cruelty toward the people who love her most. Yeoh plays every contradiction without resolving them, which is precisely why the performance lands so hard when the film demands emotional reckoning. Ke Huy Quan, returning to screens after a long absence, does something more quietly radical: he plays a man of bottomless patience and radical gentleness as if those qualities were a form of strength rather than a consolation prize, and the film agrees with him. His is the moral center the whole structure pivots around.\n\nStephanie Hsu, as Joy, is equally essential. She is asked to carry both the film\'s most chaotic energy and its most devastating emotional register, sometimes within the same scene, and she holds both without the seams showing. Jamie Lee Curtis, meanwhile, commits to absurdity with a freedom that younger actors rarely allow themselves, and the result is one of the most unexpectedly moving supporting performances in recent memory.\n\nThe Daniels work in a register that is genuinely difficult to categorize. The film swings between physical slapstick involving trophy props, wrenching maternal drama, and long stretches of something close to Buddhist philosophical inquiry — and the tonal whiplash is not always perfectly managed. There are passages in the film\'s middle hour where the chaos starts to feel slightly routine, where the next universe-hop arrives before the previous one has fully settled. The film asks a lot of its audience\'s attention and occasionally strains it. At 140 minutes, a few sequences could be trimmed without the whole losing anything essential.\n\nBut the screenplay, which is the film\'s deepest achievement, pulls everything back together. The central conceit — that confronting the infinite possibility of every life unlived is what breaks a person, and that choosing this specific life anyway is what saves them — is not a new idea philosophically. What is new is how completely the film earns it. By the time the argument resolves, it has been dramatized through action sequences, quiet kitchen conversations, animated rocks, and a performance of \"Clair de Lune\" that somehow functions as a thesis statement. The fact that any of this coheres at all is remarkable.\n\nThe film is for anyone who has ever felt that the life they are living is not quite the life they were supposed to have, and for anyone who has turned that feeling outward onto the people closest to them. It is not particularly for audiences seeking conventional narrative satisfaction or tidy emotional release. The Daniels want something messier and more honest than catharsis — they want the sensation of deciding, despite everything, to be here. That is harder to dramatize than it sounds, and this film does it."
    }
