    review: {
      themes: ["duality", "deception", "loyalty", "corruption", "masculinity", "betrayal", "identity", "surveillance"],
      mood: ["paranoid", "electric", "tense"],
      fullReview: "South Boston. Two young men climb into opposite institutions — one a state trooper embedded in the Irish mob, one a career criminal embedded in the Massachusetts State Police — and both spend the next two and a half hours certain that the walls are closing in. Martin Scorsese\'s The Departed is built around this mirror-image premise, adapted from the Hong Kong thriller Infernal Affairs, and what it does with that architecture is one of the cleaner acts of sustained genre filmmaking the decade produced.\n\nThe film operates almost entirely on dread. Not horror-movie dread — something more specific and more mundane: the particular exhaustion of performing a version of yourself so different from the real one that you begin to lose the thread of where the performance ends. Both Billy, the cop, and Colin, the criminal, are holding something in their chests the entire runtime, and the film understands that this kind of sustained deception is not exciting. It is grinding. DiCaprio, who had rarely looked this wrung-out on screen, builds Billy from the inside out — not a hero figure operating covertly, but a man unraveling in slow motion, running out of places to put the pressure. His scenes with Martin Sheen carry a quiet desperation that the louder set pieces can only gesture toward.\n\nMatt Damon has the more counterintuitive task: playing someone whose rot is entirely interior, whose surface projects such reliable competence that the film has to work to remind the audience that Colin is not the protagonist of a cop procedural. He does it cleanly. The danger in the role was always that Colin would read as simply villainous — a device rather than a person — and Damon refuses that. The character has genuine charm, genuine anxiety, genuine need. His corruption is not theatrical. It is practical.\n\nAnd then there is Jack Nicholson as Frank Costello, which is a performance that has divided people since the film opened and will continue to. There are scenes where Nicholson plays Costello as a man who enjoys being Costello — who has so thoroughly inhabited the role of South Boston patriarch-monster that the role has replaced whatever was beneath it. In those scenes he is magnetic and precise. There are other scenes where Nicholson appears to be doing something closer to freestyle, working at a register that the film around him cannot quite absorb. The instinct, one suspects, was to make Costello genuinely frightening — someone whose appetites are ungovernable — and the result is uneven in a way that the supporting cast, uniform in its tightness, makes more apparent. Mark Wahlberg, in fewer scenes than the principal players, produces the film\'s most electrically specific performance: Dignam as barely contained contempt with a badge, every line delivery landing slightly harder than it needs to, which is exactly right.\n\nWilliam Monahan\'s screenplay is the engine and it is an exceptional piece of adaptation work. The dialogue moves the way Boston itself moves — compressed, rhythmically aggressive, affectionate toward profanity in a way that feels structural rather than decorative. The plotting is intricate without feeling mechanical; the parallel reveals are timed with genuine craft. Where the script occasionally stumbles is in the Vera Farmiga subplot, which asks the film to believe that one woman, by coincidence, is entangled with both moles simultaneously. Farmiga plays it with more dignity than the construction probably deserves, but the contrivance sits there, visible.\n\nScorsese, shooting with Michael Ballhaus at his shoulder, keeps the film feeling like a city that knows its own shadows. The editing, by Thelma Schoonmaker, is where the film truly lives — she gives each scene exactly as much time as it needs and not a frame more, which in a film running two and a half hours is harder than it sounds. The pace never drags, even when the film is in the middle of a quiet conversation in a parking garage. That is a technical achievement worth naming plainly.\n\nThe ending is blunt in a way that still provokes argument. Whether it reads as nihilism, as irony, as something more ambivalent about the institutions the film has been examining — that is a question each viewer resolves differently, and the film earns the fact that it does not resolve it for them. What is not ambivalent is that for most of its runtime, The Departed is one of the more satisfying American crime films made in this century: confident in its world, alive to the specific texture of its characters, and genuinely invested in the proposition that the line between cop and criminal is less about virtue than about which side of a particular arrangement you entered from."
    }
